# Frontend MVP Conventions

## UX Priorities
- Keep screens simple, readable, and fast to scan.
- Implement the core flow first: auth, onboarding, daily dashboard.
- Show clear loading, empty, and error states for each dashboard section.
- Prefer clean UX decisions over visual complexity.
- Build frontend only after stable backend contracts are defined.
- Keep route guards strict:
  - guests -> `Login`, `Signup`
  - authenticated users -> `Onboarding` and `Dashboard` (based on onboarding status)

## Component and State Design
- Prefer small components with clear responsibilities.
- Keep method and handler names in simple English.
- Avoid over-abstraction; extract shared logic only when repeated and useful.
- Keep code readable and easy to refactor.
- Use explicit panel-level states so one failing section does not block the whole dashboard.

## API and Fallback Behavior
- Integrate free APIs only and handle rate limits/errors gracefully.
- Provide visible fallback content if news, price, AI insight, or meme endpoints fail.
- Never block the whole dashboard because one section fails.
- Access backend through stable client/service interfaces to support provider swaps.
- Use typed `apiClient` wrappers for all backend endpoints.
- Keep UI aligned with envelope parsing (`ok`, `data`, `error`) and section-level error fields.

## Model Workflow
- Prefer Composer for generating UI pages/components and styling refinements.
- Use contract-first Composer prompts that include:
  - component/page purpose
  - props and expected payload shape
  - loading/empty/error states
  - navigation/redirect behavior

## Clean Structure
- Do not create unnecessary files or folders.
- Add new frontend files only when they improve clarity or reuse.
